Food inflation in Europe has spiked
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the steady rise in food prices.
The November price growth in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, with annual inflation of 3.1% in October, after 2.6%, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate, as the reduction would, together with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation below 2%, but close to that.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must "deter" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation of 3.3 percent was a 15-year high; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has been pushed upwards by soaring food and energy prices.
The price of wheat has risen 88 percent, and the price of soybeans has reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay substantially more for edible oil and dairy products.
Oil prices on world markets have risen 52 percent this year, and last month, a barrel of black gold was already worth nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% in 2008 to 2.5% in 2009, but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate will remain at around 3 percent over the next 3-4 months, but its annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
