In many places, disinfectants are being saved
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were reported in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff in the disease control system are not helping, says the head of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, there is also a saving in disinfectants.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were discovered in a man who was hospitalized after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site earlier this year.
The patient who was seriously injured in a car accident was released home, but soon afterward he had to return with an MRSA infection, and because of the bacteria in his body, one major operation was still not possible.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-drug resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, director of the National Epidemiological Centre.
That means that so many MDR infections have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, the rest are unknown.
Almost two thirds (683) of the infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant golden staphylococcus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by one third of the human population through the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e. g. strep throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, morning infections) respond well to antibiotics and are well treated.
However, if antibiotics are given in excess or inappropriately, the bacteria that respond well to the antibiotic will develop into bacteria that are highly resistant to the antibiotics and that spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
In particular, in patients with weakened immune systems, low body weight or in elderly patients, it can cause serious hospital infections, such as morning sickness or sepsis, if the immune system is temporarily or permanently dysfunctional.
According to the chief medical officer of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing unusual about MRSA infection, and similar infections are commonplace in hospitals.
"Infection should not be confused with epidemic, MRSA is not confined to those areas", stated Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the pathogen is not investigated".
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the healthcare staff treats them in rubber gloves and masks, and we have the antibiotics we need to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to hospital are first tested for MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital MRSA infections could be prevented, but the current conditions in home hospitals are not conducive to preventing the emergence and spread of multi-drug resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection is predominantly found in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
Microbiological sampling in Hungarian hospitals is not the fashion.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund this study is also a factor.
Most cases are detected if the patient has a noticeable MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, pathologies.
Efforts should be made to target antibiotic therapy, or to conduct microbiological testing to prevent the development of drug resistance, but hospitals do not always follow this.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in primary and outpatient treatment, said Karolina Böröcz.
Saving on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most commonly spread among patients through healthcare professionals.
Hence, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but these are also seriously lacking in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and by touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in home hospitals.
In contrast, rooms are often crowded, and beds are often very close together, although from an epidemiological point of view patients should be kept at least 1.5 metres apart.
As Karolina Böröcz noted, unfortunately, we may also see hospitals in poor financial conditions cutting back on disinfectants, with few nurses and many patients, increasing the chances of infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are observed, there is a demonstrable decrease in such infections or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treating MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, so it's being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has put in place a programme to prevent MRSA, or to reduce its incidence.
The programme seems to be a success, with the release of data showing that MRSA infections in England are on a declining trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) places the prevention of the emergence of multiresistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these pathogens as one of its priorities.
