Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased the risk of the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was established with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért in August of this year, have increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several ways, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Political Capital Institute.
The company's 'risk warning' states that the greatest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that 'violent ethnic clashes may soon occur as a result of the intensification of the already existing ethnic tension between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary'.
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to be aimed at provoking such action, the research institute adds.
He writes that this can be explained by one of the greatest negligence of Hungarian political representatives: "the public discussion on the Roma question was left to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could base their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict".
This deepens the problem, prevents normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflict, the institute said.
In addition, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, influenced by the great attention of both domestic and foreign media, "have to a great extent distorted the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards belief in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity", according to the Research Institute.
The Institute recalls that part of the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which has been gaining more publicity and vehemence since autumn 2006, is that several organisations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, which call themselves 'National Defence' associations.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly declaring - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in case of natural disasters, attacks on the homeland, disruption of order), in addition to pointing to the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state", he adds.
He further notes: this is all happening in a way that tries to wrap up various political efforts based on society's resistance to politics and parties in civilian clothes.
The emphasis on the citizenship and form of the association is therefore not only a means of avoiding the legal obstacles of judicial registration in the case of such groups, but also a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been pointed out in several neighboring countries as a potential source of danger, and ultra-nationalist politicians in some neighboring countries have sought to excuse their own anti-Hungarian policies by referring to the creation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this may have an impact on the political stability of the region", he adds.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not an isolated phenomenon, so it has increased political risks for the region as a whole.
He writes that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is similar to, for example, the activities of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the formation of the Bulgarian Guard is the mass Roma riots that broke out in one of Sofia's districts (Krasna Polyana).
The BNU used this to form the Guardia, saying that the organization's goal is "national defense".
She says that during the past 17 years, Bulgaria has experienced "gypsy terror", but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, recalls the Political Capital Institute.
He adds that the initiative has sparked a stormy debate among the Bulgarian public.
The increase in the risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the announcement by some Bulgarian Roma organizations that they will form their own guards as a sign of resistance.
Since the activities of the Hungarian Guard so far show similarities with those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it is not excluded that the Hungarian Roma will respond to the threat in a similar way, by setting up their own national guard, as we can read in the risk warning prepared by the Political Capital Institute.
Attila Juhász, research director of the Political Capital Institute, said that risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
