Holidays are not free everywhere
In Hungary, the days of rest are strictly regulated by law and it has become common practice to move working days around the holidays, which will be less frequent next year.
The European Union and America have different holidays.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and days of rest.
The days off are usually associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate New Year's Day: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are a holiday - on New Year's Day, people can rest after New Year's Eve.
We have a total of 11 holidays during the year.
The national holidays are 15 March, commemorating the 1848 revolution, and 23 October, commemorating the 1956 revolution.
On August 20th we celebrate the founding of the state, May 1st we celebrate labor, November 1st and 2nd we commemorate the dead relatives and friends.
Besides, we have two-day holidays, Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our national, state, or religious holidays rarely fall on weekends, it has become a practice to shift the working day in cases where we work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price of extended weekends, of course, is that we stay at work and school the Saturday before.
The time for the day immediately preceding or following the holiday to be worked out has been regulated for many years by a special decree of the Minister of Labour.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, to civil servants and to public servants.
It does not, however, apply to undertakings and institutions which are in operation without interruption or which, for their own purposes, operate on working days.
This year, the change in the work schedule will take place just around the end of the year: from 24 December, life in the country will almost stop, as experience has shown that most people "work" in advance or take advantage of the holidays they have saved between Christmas and New Year's Day.
Next year, we're going to have a few holidays in the middle of the week, so there's less shift work than this year.
The first time, the calendar will be changed around Labor Day, so that workers can stay home for four days of trial.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2, can be a day of rest.
Another shift is due to the holiday of 23 October: Saturday 18 October will be the working day instead of Friday 24.
The end of the year, however, will be a holiday for the next year, since New Year's Day falls on Wednesday, but from December 24 on, almost everywhere will be a nonstop holiday.
