The crisis is not just in America
"All I wanted was to make money for my bank", he says in the deposition.
He managed to make half a billion euros during the summer of the American crisis.
He sensed the opportunity at the beginning of the year.
In February, reports began to emerge that so-called sub-prime mortgages, provided to low-income clients or those who had had problems with repayment in the past, would be in trouble.
The whole economy was not meant to be affected by this crisis.
Kerviel didn't believe it and he bet it right.
By the end of the year, its profit had climbed to 1.6 billion euros.
"I didn't know how to announce it when I made my first half a billion", Kerviel admits, adding that he hadn't kept anything for himself.
He admits throughout the interrogation that he falsified the records so that he wouldn't be found.
He even managed to fool his bosses, even as the Eurex stock exchange became interested in his trades.
The risk was the gain.
Was he afraid he'd be found out?
I guess not.
"I thought the simple fact that I made $1.6 billion for the bank would satisfy them".
Where did he get the will to take that risk?
He had to work his way up in his position.
He joined Société Générale in 2000 shortly after graduating from the University of Lyon.
His annual salary was about $51,000.
Two years later, he was an assistant broker, and in 2005, he became a freelance broker with a salary of $90,000 a year.
Yet he knew he would never make as much as the others.
"I knew I was being watched from my first interview in 2005.
For my education and also for my professional and personal development", Kerviel told investigators.
But soon after the launch, the first big breakthrough came.
Allianz's stock was profitable, because during the London bombings, he bet half a billion euros on the loss of the title.
And that was the trigger mechanism -- he wanted more.
While you're making money, we'll let you
"It's like a snowball", he told the police.
But the bosses said they knew everything, or they suspected it.
"While I was making money, they were blindfolded".
But then came the early morning of this year.
He lost a billion euros in one day.
He wanted to wipe it out after the weekend in mid-January.
When he came to work on Monday, he was no longer working at the bank.
And the bank reported a few days later that it had lost five billion euros.
How did they find him?
He became a suspect because of his vacation.
"I've only picked four days for the past year.
