Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the crisis in the financial markets together.
This will bring over $100 billion into the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, banks bid at the interest rate at which they are willing to lend money.
For example, the U.S. Federal Reserve will send $40 billion to auction, and the other $24 billion will be made available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated approach to prevent or mitigate the effects of the financial crisis.
"This move is to address the economy's biggest problem, namely the growing shortage of free capital that banks could lend", Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group wrote in his client report.
"Coordinated central bank action has reduced the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent", Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion in defaulted loans, primarily in the United States.
Analysts are expecting billions more to go.
"Central banks must be really worried about what might still follow if they decide to take this action", said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad", he added.
Central banks are concerned that if they have difficulty accessing loans themselves, they will be reluctant to lend to their customers.
That would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with potential impacts on global economic growth.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for lending money on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still wary of lending money to each other, even though the central banks of the United States, Canada, and Britain had cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another rate cut", Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central bank's move will help to alleviate the crisis, because it does not solve the fundamental problem, which is the collapse of the U.S. housing market.
Klaus: The environmental debate is incredible
Global climate change is set to hurt the developing countries the most.
President Václav Klaus has once again spoken out on the issue of global warming.
The criticism has now been lifted at the closing UN international conference on climate change in Bali.
In Vienna, where he presented his book Blue, Not Green Planet, he said that the debates of environmentalists are incredible.
According to Klaus, the unacceptable is not only the structure of the conference, which is a strange mix of representatives of governments and NGOs, but also the fundamental difference between the rhetoric that accompanies it and reality.
"The debate there is completely unstructured, it's just a fireworks display of words that are substitutes for solutions to current problems", Klaus said.
The Czech president, when presenting his book, stressed that the subject matter is very important to him and that is why he is so committed to it.
He also expressed satisfaction that the book appeared in a German translation, because, he said, "I often meet only with caricatures of my views".
