Klaus reminded him that although he is not a climate scientist, he feels qualified to write such a book.
He is an academic, able to monitor and evaluate professional papers, has experience in statistics and is also a national economist.
The main conclusions of the book were that the climate is constantly changing and therefore normal, that there is no consensus among all scientists on global warming, that the consequences of current changes are not too great and serious and therefore do not pose a threat, and that efforts to influence climate change are unnecessary, ineffective and unacceptably costly.
Furthermore, as a person who has experienced totalitarianism, he finds it unacceptable to impose unproven opinions on others, which he feels is a dangerous restriction on freedom.
He repeatedly explained to those present that he was not against "reasonable environmental protection, but against militant environmentalism, which does not take into account the relationship between cost and benefit".
