Congress approved the transposition of MiFID effective as of November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary deliberations, which ended today with a vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has submitted to public hearing a regulation that develops the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of the Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee investor protection and the detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the efficient functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will allow the provision of financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory firms (AFI) that are linked to securities companies, securities intermediaries and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of financial instruments is being expanded by the addition of multilateral trading and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with existing stock exchange brokers.
The law also obliges investment firms to disseminate information on the market on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk mitigation methods and requires them to keep a record of all operations carried out in order to simplify supervision by the CNMV.
During the Congressional Trade Committee hearing, several amendments were made, notably to make securitised receivables a "complex" financial instrument given the high risk to the investor, as demonstrated by what happened in the US with subprime mortgages.
The transposition of the Directive has also been used to legally define the functions that bachelors in economics and business administration can hold, 30 years after the Royal Decree of 1977 which defined the professional functions reserved for economists.
The Senate also ordered the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require authorisation from the CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for different investment firms simultaneously.
