Concerns over a new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
The dispute over gas prices between Russia and Ukraine is ongoing, raising the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is piped through Ukraine and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev warned that if Moscow raises gas prices to Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous dispute between the two last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more, as it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for gas it obtains from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations", Ukraine's Economy Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
'The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit charges (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.'
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev led to a reduction in Gazprom's supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a sharp drop in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices up sharply.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the EU's gas supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
