The NHS Chamber is expected to check foreign staff for qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK before they are employed.
Although the Scottish Health Service uses Disclosure Scotland for criminal records checks, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report of the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that the commissions should be guided by the guidelines of the Criminal Records Bureau, which assists employers with audits in several countries.
"Although we found that some of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out regularly", the report said.
Mr Black said that the Scottish NHS was in many ways in line with its own pre-employment checks policy, but added: 'Our report points out areas where the system could be improved to ensure accurate information on the number of foreign staff is available.'
Dr Peter Terry, chairman of the BMA Scotland, said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS staff who might commit a terrorist act in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-employment checks in the Scottish NHS are working well and it is not clear what further value the comments will bring", he said.
The Scottish Health Authority has announced that it currently has 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
