The climate on Venus may be a glimpse into the future of Earth
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus may have once been a pleasant place for life.
Data from the European orbiting station show that the planet is even more like the Earth's stubborn twin than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit on similar orbits, but Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus had conditions similar to Earth's and could have been habitable.
But the accelerated greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and slower rotation have sent Venus down a completely different path of evolution.
Today, the planet is waterless, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it's being devastated by hurricane-force storms and winds.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which studied the planet for a year, offer a sober glimpse of how the Earth might evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission said: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario where Venus began as did Earth, possibly with habitable environments, billions of years ago".
