Two months ago, when the Prime Minister avoided calling an election and insulted British intelligence by claiming that the decision was not influenced by the poll, there was hope that he would secure a resilient and effective government.
Instead of the increasingly funny line from the acting Liberal Democrat leader, the once-feared Mr Brown has changed from Stalin to Mr Bean.
The reckless rescue of the troubled Northern Rock Bank has revealed weaknesses in management and poor judgment under fire.
Badly thought-out tax reform proposals have brought the corporations together against the government.
The loss of personal data on 25 million people has revealed unimaginable administrative malpractice.
Three retired generals started a revolt in the House of Lords, protesting cuts to military spending, saying that being a commander of the armed forces was a part-time job.
Now, here are the gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour general secretary (and their former watchdog of internal discipline), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading for his end.
Yet governments can reach a tipping point where they find governance difficult.
People don't trust politicians, and they don't like them, but they usually shift their distrust when a new party takes over.
Once it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to make things better, and may not even be in office for long, this shift is gone: the administration becomes a loophole, ministers start briefing, the press searches for bad news, and the government becomes decentralized and defensive.
In one respect, Mr. Brown's position is particularly difficult, since he cannot take the position of the new brush compared to other political leaders.
As much as he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the Treasury records are connected to the decisions Mr. Brown made as Secretary of the Treasury.
And even though he wasn't directly involved in Blair's troubles, such as the lengthy investigation into party funding caused by "value for money", voters can safely assume he was.
Mr. Brown's troubles are not as bad as they seem.
The overcrowding isn't as terrible as the conservatives make it.
As far as Mr. Bean is concerned, no one has been killed or deceived.
And the cure, painful as it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown's Stalinist tendencies have always promised: reliable, stable, and mildly brutal government.
The recent political donation scandal is a good example.
The garboid Mr. Abrahams, who compares his donations to charity, says he didn't want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but it wasn't his decision.
The laws against the anonymity of big political donors are clear and they exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who might be buying access to those who rule the country.
Mr Watt, who said he knew about Mr Abrahams's scheme but did not know it was illegal, will be questioned in detail, as will Jon Mendlesohn, the Labour chief fundraiser who learned about the scurrilous gifts in October.
But so far, Mr. Brown is not involved; there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these entanglements, even though the bulk of the payments were made after he took office in June.
The Prime Minister has done half the work so far.
He was quick to condemn the violation of his own party's laws, but he diluted his resolve by resorting to a well-established instrument, the commission to investigate the matter - led by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not difficult.
If the law has been broken, it is a police matter.
In addition, there are other things Mr. Brown must do, such as finding a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had none for six months, and moving forward with a real reform of party funding.
That would require the Labour Party, which is in a tight spot, to cooperate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up its special financial relationship with the unions - a bitter pill for a party loyalist like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
The Conservatives are now well ahead in the polls; he has two years to win back the voters; and the only way to win is with unassailable integrity and high competence.
Card sharks
Is the subprime mortgage crisis affecting the U.S. credit card market?
When blood is in the water, the dorsal fins naturally begin to move around excitedly.
Now that the U.S. housing market is shrinking, predators have turned their attention to the credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts say that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other consumer credit options were infected by subprime mortgages.
The signs of tension are obvious.
The number of cases of non-payment (with more than 30 days' delay) and of accounts written off (accounts considered non-enforceable by the provider) is increasing.
HSBC announced last month that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer lending market - also due to nonperforming credit card loans.
It's too early to panic, though.
There's still a lot of unpaid bills and insolvency.
According to Moody's, the 3.89% default rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below the average.
The deterioration rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The 2005 change in US personal bankruptcy laws led to a sharp decline in the number of bankruptcy filings, which make up the bulk of credit card losses; thus, the number of filings (and thus the number of write-offs) would increase regardless of whether the general conditions for lenders deteriorated.
The industry also shows a good repayment rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts each month.
And confidence in securities backed by credit cards is solid, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr. Dennis Moroney of the research firm TowerGroup predicts that their emissions volumes in 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
There are definitely direct routes for the spread of infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when they dry up on loans for real estate, consumers tend to get into credit card debt.
Credit card issuers, however, look more to cash flow than to collateral values, so falling house prices may not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of lenders.
They can even be advantageous to lenders.
The incentive for consumers to repay mortgages decreases as the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, card debt moves up the priority list for repayment.
Card issuers can also respond more quickly and flexibly to more volatile conditions than mortgage lenders by changing interest rates or borrowing limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risks of rapid price fluctuations of the warranty items.
"We're not going to have to reassess all our loans overnight", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
While the risk of a subprime-style explosion is low, the risk of a gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower house prices and debt reduction push America into recession, the credit card industry faces a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
British bankers plead guilty in the Enron case
Three British bankers who were due to stand trial for their roles in a fraudulent scheme linked to former Enron chief executive Andrew Fastow changed their plea to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew originally denied seven counts of fraud, involving them and Fastow in financial fraud in 2000 -- getting rich off their employers' accounts.
They were due in court in January.
However, during the trial before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein, Jr., each of them confessed to one fraud.
The case of the three former senior executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, was front-page news for the two years of the issuance proceedings.
In the United States, their case is one of the unfinished parts of an investigation that began after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The charges brought against them in 2002 alerted Mr. Fastow to the fact that he was the target of a government investigation into the Enron collapse.
The indictment against the bankers -- who have earned the nickname "NatWest Three" -- alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to plot a fraud with Fastow and his former top aide Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in a subsidiary of Enron controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of a series of Enron scams that propelled Enron into a spiral of bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank valued its stake in this branch at zero, but our three British people knew that it was in fact of considerable value.
The company under Kopper's control bought a stake in the bank's branch for $1 million.
The accused bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in this subsidiary of Greenwich NatWest.
But the 20 million actually went to those British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, according to the indictment, and Fastow, Kopper and others adjusted for approximately $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the collapse of Enron.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence at a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence at a facility in Texas.
All three British men were free on $1 million bail, which ordered them to remain in the United States for the upcoming trial.
Enron, once the seventh-largest company in the country, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks no longer allowed it to hide billions in debt or report failed speculations as profitable.
The collapse has lost thousands of jobs, over $60 billion in market value and over $2 billion in pension insurance.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company's collapse.
Skilling is serving more than 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were vacated after he died of heart disease last year.
Moscow's powerlessness
The price of the Gulfstream G550, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and with enough fuel to fly nonstop from Moscow to Los Angeles, starts at $54 million.
For some of Russia's rich, it's a small return.
"It can carry up to 18 passengers", says Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of them are interested in that many seats, because it's for a close family or a corporate president".
Mr. Firer was sitting in the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire's Fair, which is a four-day orgy of lavish consumption at the mammoth exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, over 200 other luxury suppliers set up stalls, hoping to lure the newly wealthy Russians to everything from mahogany-lined yachts to diamond-lined racks to cars that 50 Cent wouldn't be ashamed of.
Mr. Firer looked carefully at the bright orange Porsche in the side stall.
"It's a nice car, but they're against us in fifths and tenths", he said.
"Russia is the second largest private jet market after the United States".
The oil waves are pouring money into the Russian capital just like they did in Dallas' days.
"We passed the same stage in the 1980s when some Americans got enormously rich and moved to Europe, where they were looked at as materialists", said Marshall Goldman, a fourth-year student at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard.
Like the Saudi spenders of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, the Russians are becoming the world's most prominent spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their work on this Klondike.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, the luxury industry conference drew Donatello Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of the LVMH group, to exchange ideas on how to sell expensive goods in markets like the Russian one.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, which is owned by The New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires with a combined fortune of $282 billion, according to Forbes magazine's list of the richest people.
In addition, the Center for Economic and Financial Research, a leading local institute, published a report on the development of personal wealth in the former Soviet Union, which found that there are 103,000 "second-rate" millionaires in Russia, with a combined fortune of $670 billion.
(The World Bank reports that in 2005 15.8% of Russians lived below the subsistence level.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow -- and that's why we're all here", said Nicole Marais, sales and marketing representative for London jeweller David Morris.
She was at the fair for the first time, along with the Russian distributor of the brand, Soho Jewelry Group.
"All women are well-groomed and men are well-off".
Walking around in their evening gowns on Sunday night in their hats, 21-year-old Evgenia Yumatova and five-year-old Svetlana Turovtsova branded themselves and their clients millionaires.
"I've been looking at these cars and I can't decide between an Infiniti, a Mercedes and a Porsche", said Ms. Yumatova, who was wearing a red carpet veteran's branded outfit, next to which Joan Rivers looked like a housewife.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at the freshly rich, brand-driven Russian shoppers who are willing to sit for hours in road traffic to stroll through a warehouse that is a crisp mix of Cadillac Escalade, platinum fish, Mövenpick ice cream, bespoke pool tables, Dubai apartments, Gund stuffed animals and a caravan.
Members of the public could purchase tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"The Russians are interested in which brand is the most expensive and the best", said Mr. Gijrath, who patriotically occupied the booth of the Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft before reproducing Rembrandt's painting of hand-painted blue tiles in life-size.
"Of course the Russians are more interested in gold".
And indeed, the sellers here say that the Russians with the old money (by Russian standards it's 10 to 15 years old) have already moved from flashy logos to little-known limited edition brands that would never be shown at the shopping fair.
Yet, thousands of people, whether millionaires, millionaire emissaries, or tourists, flooded the trade fairs every day.
And some of them were shopping.
On the first day of the exhibition, last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the local general manager of King Koil beds, said he sold two sets of mattresses made of silk, cashmere and cotton, braided with gold thread, for $70,000 each.
Also on the first day, Mikhail Lyubimov, sales manager of A1 Moto, which equips high-end cars with high-end alarms, said that his company sold a bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
On Sunday afternoon, Andrej Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a luxury car customizer, said he had sold three chainsaw-style car grids for a Rolls-Royce Phantoma for $55,000.
He showed the reporter a wheel of a car designed for the Russian casino owner, which was to be splattered with Swarovski crystals so that it looked like roulette.
Price: $22,000 for four of these.
"The Russian millionaire who wants a wheel made of ostrich skin or a portrait of his wife made of cubic zirconia does not have to ride those wheels yet", said Mr. Karapetian.
"He'll keep them in his garage for 30 to 40 cars".
While many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaire" doesn't mean much of an exclusive nowadays, given the huge increase in property prices here.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash", he said.
"There are more than you think".
Those who aren't millionaires could at least pretend to be rich at a booth run by Russian asset management firm Alliance Continental.
The company erected four red British-style telephone booths filled with a pile of counterfeit bills worth a million dollars.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing manager, said that his team had printed 500,000 counterfeit bills for the Millionaires' Fair.
Passersby stopped to throw a pile of money around, or to have their friends take a picture with their cell phone as they relaxed amidst the surplus wealth, or simply to stuff their pockets with a few million.
"You know, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire", said Mr. Karryev.
