The hope of the Fed cutting interest rates leads to a strengthening of the world's stock markets
Stock prices on both sides of the Atlantic jumped yesterday as market hopes that the Fed would try to ease lending conditions by further cutting interest rates were bolstered by reassuring remarks from the vice president of the US central bank.
Stock markets jumped in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, second only to Ben Bernanke, the Fed chairman, said that in response to continued pressure on financial markets, regulators must be "flexible and pragmatic".
In an apparent effort to calm the agitated markets amid signs of a reviving credit effort, Mr Kohn said that the recent upheavals "partly reversed some improvements in the functioning of the markets towards the end of September and in October".
It also stated that if the increased instability persists, there is a greater chance that the financial conditions of households and firms will deteriorate further.
