England must decide, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
We have two dilemmas, one almost as difficult as the other.
Who's going to be number six at bat for England this weekend in Kandy, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, in a wider context no less relevant than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who is to make this decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, the chairman of the selection committee, who is holding the post on loan at best, has Peter Moores, the head coach, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, to help with the decision-making and because the desk of Hugh Morris, the general manager of the England team, is starting to fill with applications for the post of national selector, though not necessarily full-time.
Whoever doesn't get a sixth on the bat is going to be unlucky, but life is often unfair, and sports are not.
It's not easy to find what gets one to the top of their profession, while someone else never gets past the lower level, sometimes due to lack of luck rather than ability.
It's not just in cricket that the choice is difficult and requires judgment, which in the end always has to be subjective.
Is this the right time for Bopara to move up?
Is it fair to the Shah if it is?
We could ask the same thing in another field, say here: John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both smart young executives with good education and industry experience, should be promoted to the board -- there's only one seat.
Who's to say which level is right for a cricketer when he can't get a chance to go down or swim to the next?
Naturally, numbers have a big influence on decision-making, but so do opportunities.
In a team, a cricketer has to catch the captain's eye at the right moment to take the wicket, and a batsman needs regular chances in the starting positions if he ever wants to make an impression as a one-day cricketer.
Catching a picker's gaze is more complicated.
For example, last season, there were many better than James Anderson, whose place in the first Test seems certain, even if Stephen Harmison declared himself healthy and threw like an archer.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets at 33 runs apiece.
Chris Tremlett took just 29 at the same modest average, but both had their moments at the highest level and are hoping for the next.
Whether he plays at Asgiriya Shah Stadium or Bopara may be a matter of opinion.
The choice may spark or affect the careers of both, or it may not have much impact.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played every Test and in first-class he gave good performances, five wickets and 40 free runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, who at the same time was fighting for his place, who eventually became a stable Test cricketer, who is in addition, although in Australia against Australia he scored twice a hundred, perhaps still underestimated.
It's more likely that Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after one more discussion following today's training at the Asirgiya Stadium, will follow their conservative instincts and prefer Shah's greater experience to Bopar's youthful exuberance.
There are arguments for both.
Speaking for Shah, his sparkling and valuable debut Test turn at 88 in Mumbai and 32 centuries in first-class against six by Bopar, who, at 22, is seven years younger and has an excellent stat against spin bowls.
However, Shah made just ten runs in two innings in May against the Caribbean in a Test at Lord's, his home ground in Middlesex, and this, coupled with the immediate rejection of the selectors when Vaughan wanted to re-sign him for the next match, his kicking seems to have taken something from the momentum that was so evident in Bombay.
But the Essex Universals have the joie de vivre in their bones.
He is not intimidated by anything on the cricket field, and his behavior off the field is symbolic of a recently overturned four-wheel drive car at the show day of the car sponsor of the English team, Volkswagen.
He was left with minor injuries and apparently in shock, but the first thing he did was pull out his Vodafone (also sponsored, of course) and call Alastair Cook, his teammate who was watching from a distance, to ask him excitedly, "Did you see that?"
Bopara is definitely better in the field, his medium-fast slip shots on the pitches here, which seem to suit him, he delivers effectively and he shoots confidently and skillfully.
Picking the right person is one thing, picking the right time is another.
Maybe that's the real art of choice.
Personally, I'm inclined to give Bopara his chance now, which is not to say that Shah won't excel if, as the Ceylon tea tickets suggest, he's the one who's playing next weekend.
