Venus is the Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more Earth-like than previously thought. The European spacecraft Venus Express on Venus has recorded phenomena that occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that lightning strikes on Venus.
Now the European Venus Express probe has provided evidence - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere, and on Venus, lightning flies from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 35 miles [56 km], writes Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific journal Nature.
The theory of primordial matter is that life on Earth could have been created by lightning storms that triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
That was not the case on Venus: "If life ever existed there, it must have been a long time ago", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, life would be scarce on the surface of Venus, with an atmosphere about 100 times as dense as Earth's, and temperatures sometimes as high as 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be the hellish twin of Earth, but it is a twin", said Russell.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, began to evolve in a completely different way is a fundamental question of the ESA mission.
Since no spacecraft have been sent to study Venus exclusively since the early 1990's, the launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 marked a milestone in the planet's exploration.
According to scientists, the latest research results, which were reported in several articles in Nature, did more than emphasize Venus' uniqueness in the solar system.
"They also showed that our neighboring planet is more like Earth than previously thought", Esa said.
In addition to the already known North Pole vortices, scientists have found a cloud vortex at the South Pole that spins much faster.
This phenomenon resembles air currents in the Earth's northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics, Space and Cosmic Physics.
The second innermost planet in our solar system is almost as massive as Earth, and at 12,100 kilometers in diameter, it's almost as big.
This planet, known as Dawn or Evening Star, orbits the sun in almost 225 days.
But it spins much slower around its own axis, so a day on Venus is 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus' surface temperature is not as high as Earth's, at 460 degrees Celsius and 92 bars, scientists believe that the two planets formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both, but on Earth it remained in the oceans, while on Venus it evaporated into space.
While carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonates on Earth, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
