These aren't Warhol boxes.
Whoever combines the words Sweden and wooden boxes is not thinking of Andy Warhol, but of Ike.
Or is it?
The wooden boxes currently made in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Most of his list of 94 Stockholm-type "Brillo boxes" are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen raised doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's 1968 "Brillo boxes" a few months ago, an internal investigation by the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has come up with a disappointing result: six "Brillo boxes" donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultén are copies - as are most of the other Stockholm-style "Brillo boxes" in circulation on the international art market.
The events that precede are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-and-white design of Brillo's paper soap powder boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes, which were not supplied by Warhol for financial reasons, but were supplied directly from the Brillo factory.
It wasn't about the artwork, it was about the exhibits, just the exhibits.
Warhol also apparently gave permission in 1968 for several wooden Brillo boxes to be made in Sweden, but these are not on display at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time now speak of 15 boxes that went down in art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" labeled Type Stockholm.
Some of them have been auctioned off for over $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred boxes were made and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left him.
In fact, 105 Hultén boxes were only produced in Malmö for the exhibition in St. Petersburg in 1990.
By then, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, Lars Byström, the head curator of the Moderna Museet, examined three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood panels were painted with base paint and brushed, were painted with oil white.
On the other hand, the structure of the 1990 copies showed that the paint was applied by a painter's roll directly to the polishing plate without prior basic painting - and it is acrylic, not oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list", Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve was quoted as saying: "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York reaches a different conclusion, Moderna Museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as 'copy material.'"
Back in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "primary allegations" made in the case of the soapbox.
But the organization has remained relentlessly silent.
